6. Vivet extento Proculeius aevo] Pro- culeius is stated by the Scholiasta to have assisted his brothers Caepio aud Murena, who had lost their property in the civil wars. Scipio, as the name ap in Ascen- sius’ text of the Scholiasts, is a mistalte for Caepio. But it is doubtful whether Caepio, whose family name was Fannius, was any relation of Proculeius Murena whose con· spiracy he joined (see Introduction), or whether Murena was Proculeius’ brother or cousin. Proculeius was in great favour with Augustus and was intimate with Maecenas (who married his sister or cousin Terentia), and probably with Sallustius. He was alive at this time, and did not die till aflaer Horace3 therefore the reading ⁴ agit ' which is that of many old MSS. is rejected by most editors. Proculeius was like Maecenas a favourer of letters, aud is so referred to by Juvenal (S. vii. 94) ε “ Quis tibi Maecenas quis nunc erit aut Proculeius ?”
